The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together they have 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, Sunday&#39;s early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of both parties to the current grand coalition and a significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People&#39;s Party (ÖVP) has suffered particularly heavy losses, shaking the position of current chairman Wilhelm Molterer.
On the contrary, the election leader of the Association for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian governor Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, it remains the strongest party in the Social Democratic Republic (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the vote, but is losing 5.5 percent of the vote against the last elections in 2006.
The ÖVP fared even worse, losing almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these great parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially among the people who caused the early elections, they were literally a catastrophic result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People&#39;s Party had a considerable advantage over the SPÖ in preferences.
However, voters have apparently punished them for letting the government go bankrupt.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of the party chairman and current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party&#39;s presidency.
Such a development would probably facilitate the way to the still most probable way out of the election result, ie to renew the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
However, due to the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Free (FPÖ) won 18 percent and the BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed concern about the repeat of 1999, when the People&#39;s Party agreed with the populists (the FPÖ was still united; from the BZÖ) to a joint government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and expects to return to Vienna for national politics, is clearly betting on this development.
The Green Party also got into parliament, but it lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties apparently crossed the 4% mark and did not get into parliament.
Knife-edge duel: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
From this it seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons to buy a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It&#39;s probably hard to get a top-of-the-line expensive turntable at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc&#39;s latest album.
On the one hand, such music products are not published on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if vinyls with art rock, jazz or blues are crammed into your shelves, you will probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It is the same with music on the go, ie compressed music, simply put - MP3 music.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for some people to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will probably have a hard time trying headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life also matters
Some high-end music players can handle much more than just playing music, but what most cell phones don&#39;t even happen to.
No current device is as versatile as a telephone.
In addition to its primary functions, telephoning and texting, it can play music and video, record both, it has a better, worse camera and maybe even navigate.
And when you consider smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It&#39;s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television photographs anything.
The versatility of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest eaters of energy.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
Therefore, with cheap mobile phones, expect that they will not play for you for more than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
You won&#39;t have this problem with MP3 players, even the worse ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when uploading music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With some exceptions (iPods), you don&#39;t need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players will already create a music library sorted by artist name, album name, genre or user rating.
Some devices only display a directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones know more
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output, and of course the comfort of operation.
If the music is primarily a backdrop for you and if you listen to it only briefly every day, for example on the tram, any mobile phone that plays MP3s will suffice.
Which almost any mobile phone can really do.
You don&#39;t even have to watch what music formats your mobile phone or player can do.
MP3s can handle everyone, and the vast majority of music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widespread and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online, for example.
All you have to do is visit the relevant pages of the operator (or another provider) via the mobile internet and buy a song or album.
This service in itself could be a strong argument for purchasing a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry a mobile phone with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel the mobile phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you also always carry headphones or at least a wired handsfree.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker, which has almost every mobile phone, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music mobile phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you can buy a very decent walkman.
In most cases, however, you will be limited by the absence of output to regular headphones.
The best and technically most equipped phones with a 3.5 mm jack for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest ones - not necessarily the cheapest ones (see our selection) - can be controlled by anyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of control with a previously common cassette player or, for example, a turntable, is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of an accidentally switched on mobile internet and subsequently a giant bill for data transfer.
What device to reach for
Even the cheapest mobile phones (eg Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card, you can fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you should rather reach for specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of operation is close to a separate MP3 player.
The furthest is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman phones have the same user interface as the separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours), MP3 players will take you from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic ones to become cheaper.
Maybe it won&#39;t be long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, this was also confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and a penetration well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, often reminds them of this, saying in the past several times that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably doesn&#39;t have much of a chance (after all, it would probably be hard to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which even traditional operators had to respond.
Even before the entry of pike as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, similar voices were heard in Great Britain as in our country.
But it turned out that there is a place for such operators and they can be really successful.
After all, we don&#39;t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, U: fona.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not involve relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheaply as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on a new target group can also be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
&quot;The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust,&quot; says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings. &quot;
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region, &quot;Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favor of this idea.
On the contrary, it tries to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera group has not been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time, and would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
&quot;We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to make progress with some of them in the negotiations, &quot;says Pavel Kaidl, the group&#39;s spokesman.
So maybe it&#39;s flashing for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should see the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
&quot;At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the emergence of a full - fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity with a complex and serious project in this area has approached us, &quot;said Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2&#39;s statement: &quot;So far, we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build further.&quot;
He adds: &quot;It is difficult for a virtual operator to appear in T-Mobile&#39;s network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table so that we can think in this short term. &quot;
Vodafone focuses more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: &quot;We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the most beneficial from the customer&#39;s point of view.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet. &quot;
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to start?
The fact that when operators are concerned about something, they can pull together, is also evidenced by the scramble around the creation of U: fon.
Probably the greatest pressure towards the CTU came at the time of the establishment of U: fon from the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from the CTU website.
But now U: fon is suitable as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: &quot;The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further intensified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services. &quot;
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the utter lack of interest of Czech regulators is directly striking.
At the same time, it is not just the position of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - does not have the authority to interfere in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical position on the whole issue.
&quot;The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators, &quot;said Kristián Chalupa from the Office of External Relations of the Office in response to our question.
The statement formulated in this way will probably not surprise the representatives of the operators.
From the authority, which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to make sure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than considered serious.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services.&quot;
Apparently, however, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not in the interests of the Office.
In truth, shocking in the whole case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence comes up all by itself.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly just a matter of chance and fierce competition.
&quot;The Office did not find any signs of anticompetitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, so it does not have a correspondingly increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also lacking in the telecommunications regulator, &quot;Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the CTO, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always required to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should at least be a warning to the Office that the three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
At the same time, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
The imposition of responsibility on the CTU is then a relatively common trick in telecommunications, by which the Office gives its hands away from the whole matter.
We have met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTU&#39;s powers to the area of competition in telecommunications failed to be enforced, although a number of experts promised to improve the situation.
Representatives of the Office must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It works when no one is watching
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, goes unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
&quot;If the cases you are talking about occur, it could be a breach of the terms and conditions we are dealing with and could result in termination of cooperation with the company,&quot; Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that similar activity would not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators opposes such a procedure.
They make significant profits from the activities of these companies and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: &quot;The law allows similar speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot use it fully like regular customers of mobile operators. &quot;
But that is exactly what the CTU should be at least strange about.
In addition, another question arises for the Office.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar process, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the Office has relatively strong powers to detect similar activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no idea about such a thing and their business conditions prohibit it.
When we will not be the most expensive
As has been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a noticeable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in practically all countries where virtual operators were established, classical operators tried to more or less prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it is at these moments that regulators have intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and the addition of others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case around like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot shake the impression that ambiguity in competencies is more than appropriate in these cases.
But let&#39;s not throw a shotgun into rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator appears in our country really soon, the Czech mobile market may start moving again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the Office to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other applicants.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech Statehood Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek ceremoniously presented new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj.
The anthem was newly recorded by the orchestra of the National Theater under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choral performance and instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took over the singing.
The authors of the anthem adaptations are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had deliberately chosen singers with young representative voices who are strong and popular to sing solo variants.
&quot;From the beginning, I tried to make sure that they both had a clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they agreed,&quot; he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where is my home first heard in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theater in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously took it for granted.
The first stanza of the song then became a natural part of the national anthem after the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
