The Sudetenland wanted a referendum on the United States
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded the incorporation of Šumava into the United States.
This follows from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
When we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the auspices of the United States.
Some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly turned to the US President in 1945 with such a wish.
This follows, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In a letter from the American president, the Germans from Český Krumlov ask that he not allow the return of the &quot;Šumava county&quot; - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We understood the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,&quot; reads the letter, signed &quot;People for whom the fate of Šumava is at heart&quot;.
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia allegedly gives the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national nature - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the Protectorate over Šumava for the present and eternal times.
&quot;We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million people, you would give this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and refutes minorities and has done nothing to contribute to the Allied victory,&quot; the letter said.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly fear of the revenge of the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
If the President of the USA allegedly doubts the thinking of the Šumava Germans, it was enough for him to hold a referendum in the Šumava County as to whether its inhabitants want to become part of the USA or live under the auspices of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a little naive in today&#39;s knowledge of post-war history, according to some witnesses, it aptly illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Czech Germans had to at least suspect that it would be their expulsion from the republic, few of them ever admitted such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
During the war, he was a German from Budweis deployed to the Baltic Navy.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in a prison camp in Holstein, dozens of other Czech Germans went to him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They believed that when they returned home, the Czech language would be useful to them,&quot; Chalupa said.
According to him, none of the German prisoners living in Czechoslovakia before the war expected to be expelled from the republic on the basis of Beneš&#39;s decrees.
