Even rats have feelings
When a rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have feelings as well.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same way when they behave like us?
Contributions by well-known scientists have been published in the online magazine &quot;Edge&quot; for several years.
In his series, SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question &quot;What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?&quot;
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else able to prove it when we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we begin to engage in another kind and open up questions of perception or consciousness in general, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it will do the same as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
Humans behave similarly, with some scholars suggesting a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal experience.
This is partly because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This large area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden in the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is linked to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly be affected by language, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, neither can it be measured nor, due to special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its examination presents us with great problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but in addition, there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in animal consciousness regardless of their content, and this is exactly what is the case in short-term memory studies in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, taken by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the nefrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that an emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in a brain aware of its own activities.
What we call &quot;fear&quot; is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) uses operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely linked to those areas of the cortex that characterize primates, and humans in particular.
In connection with linguistic nature, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states so that we can ascribe them side by side to others.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brainstem areas devoted to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who is more focused on the brainstem.
Because this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could easily contribute to the feelings perceived by several animal genera.
Purely theoretically, I cannot oppose it, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt in the same way by both organisms: But how can it be verified, says Pankseep, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach is fleeing from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the identity of experience.
It is true that neural comparisons take us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, while cockroaches and the brain do not.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it could be proven in humans: how would we like to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), Have feelings.
But I really don&#39;t know how to do it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I examine emotional behavior rather than the emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I do not examine language and consciousness, nor do I examine feelings, for I do not know if they exist.
It can be considered short-sighted, but I would rather move forward than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I&#39;m a practical emotionalist.
