The Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Con, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
So the tourist guides will tell you.
The building sits astride at the end of the platforms with a tower on each corner of the façade, at a sight indistinguishable from some German provincial town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the arched box office, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gateway was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to realize its ambition to control the Middle East with this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their dormitories were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
