In 1917, an explosion of an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has gradually crumbled and history is bypassing it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is engaging.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the AKP&#39;s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a jerky ride on the tracks, reminiscent of the old-world rhythms of the famous Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
She aroused suspicion in the west, especially in Washington.
A taxi drove me to AKP&#39;s main tent, an state-of-the-art stone and metal building deliberately built in a thriving suburb, surrounded by semi-detached department stores and power shops, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to do early morning business. .
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a center-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I&#39;m sure he had a Blackberry, too.
&quot;The goal of the party &#39;s foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly, &quot;he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its confines.
Today he has to look east and west at the same time.
It was no choice.
He had to do both.
&quot;But there will definitely be a time,&quot; I asked, &quot;when will Turkey have to decide?&quot;
&quot;Turkey,&quot; he said, &quot;did not want such a decision to be made.&quot;
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost by heart: Turkey&#39;s relations not only with the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as to Turkey.
