Eatonville, the first completely black town to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: &quot;a town of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prisons. &quot;
