Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Zora! Festival to pay tribute to Hurston, Harlem&#39;s most famous female writer.
The city she described remains aside, even though it has made it a tourist stop by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project during the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who &quot;knows so little about us that he doesn&#39;t even know what he&#39;s missing.&quot; . &quot;
Even today, in a year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate on race, many locals remain wary of foreign views.
&quot;We pay close attention to how our story is told,&quot; said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city&#39;s oldest parish.
&quot;It must be right.&quot;
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black rise and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak-shaded example of southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that arose from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and conservationist.
And worries about the idea of Eatonville really only started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt dialect books such as &quot;Mules and Men&quot; (1935) and &quot;Their Eyes Were Watching God&quot; (1937).
Five paragraphs of a Florida tourist guide have turned the city a short distance into Highway 17, which runs through the often overlooked center of Florida, into a stage for black history and human drama.
With the force of a big drum in life and in literature, Hurston introduced readers to the store of Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
&quot;To the left of the road,&quot; she wrote, &quot;is a white brown ornate modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds, always cared for by Howard Miller, even if he can&#39;t read or write much.&quot;
She also mentioned Dash&#39;s widow&#39;s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn &quot;sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into a one-hour hotel.&quot;
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was obviously not a typical Fodor&#39;s publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
&quot;Zora said it the way it was,&quot; says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson&#39;s choir girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang obscene songs about their beauty.
&quot;Some people didn&#39;t like it,&quot; she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a nimble eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of her dignified clothing.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many sneered.
&quot;People have always liked to see Zora,&quot; Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging in a chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, &quot;she never stayed too long.&quot;
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were taken out of print.
Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
&quot;I don&#39;t think they understood her significance for the world or her legacy at all,&quot; said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston &#39;s biography &quot;Wrapped in Rainbows,&quot; published in 2003.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to run a five-lane highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the local dual carriageway.
The Orlando crawl had already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle for racial mixing brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
&quot;At that time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on the side,&quot; Franklin said.
&quot;Actually, we had a lady here who killed it.
They threw watermelon out of the car. &quot;
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court&#39;s demand for forced integration and said of its decision in the Brown case against the Chamber of Education that it was &quot;offensive to my race rather than glorifying.&quot;
Residents now say that school desegregation, while positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of local youth.
&quot;Black kids were used to being hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,&quot; said NY Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
That lasted until teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
&quot;You don&#39;t hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there&#39;s a cultural barrier,&quot; said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, has helped create space for many other Zory Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, have risen above prejudices with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as &quot;How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!&quot;
I don&#39;t understand that. &quot;
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston&#39;s unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, the acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway came to the shelves of bookstores, and she reinstated her into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville&#39;s most famous daughter found the ramp lights again.
Hurston&#39;s former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and many return every January to celebrate.
After several years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
&quot;Those five currents of the highway resurrected, you would say it directly detonated, a real civic pride,&quot; Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: &quot;Zora saved Eatonville.&quot;
The victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Out-of-town people like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started attending the church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on the asphalted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes look like a sunken alley in summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, 90 percent are black.)
Strangers who come to look for the story and significance of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance, and certain items - such as murals in Eatonville&#39;s oldest church, painted by whites depicting blacks in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Jones, a brave, confident teacher who likes deep red, are still worried that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And as the Hurston Festival grew, so did domestic pride.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled, and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, industrious, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin&#39;s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, has a sincere love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police, which he says would receive some help.
And even younger ones, such as the eleven-year-old twins of Winter Park, Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
&quot;Most people, when they just pass through here, think, &#39;Um, this city is nothing compared to the others,&#39;&quot; Alondra Kenon said after church recently on Sunday.
&quot;But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it&#39;s a very nice city.&quot;
Here in New York, we all speak fluently financially
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn&#39;t realize they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never have guessed that in the glass beehive of offices above their heads, bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York have the worst &quot;bad day in the office&quot; since the 1929 crisis.
The messengers are still rattling with metal carts on the sidewalks, carrying muffin pans to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics are still moving between the towers, wearing, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts that hang from rockers on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it is still not possible to get a yellow taxi on weekdays between four and seven in the afternoon.
It didn&#39;t look like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this task to coincide with a late afternoon siesta at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, about twenty people were already waiting in line.
Not in front of cash registers to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of a counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy&#39;s general store, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my &quot;licensed personal banker,&quot; came for the same reason I did.
However, in contrast to me, they have already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in the places where they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They withdrew money from so-called thrifts (somewhat similar to building societies), monetary associations and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state, and which claim to take care of their customers as a family.
Last year, 15 such banks went bankrupt silently.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $ 327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers returned home for the weekend of Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $ 440 billion in assets, tried to catch a rescue buyer.
Office and shop workers standing in front of me, afraid of further collapse, moved their cash to a bank that is seen as a safe haven and that does most of the rescue on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned to be fluent in finance over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket was talking on the phone, speaking to Lehman Borthers, the bankrupt bank, and her emaciated chief executive, Dick Fuld, with such familiarity as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed roughly fifty-year-old housekeeper of my apartment building, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation - Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me: &quot;I now have my savings in money market funds.
I moved it, I won&#39;t risk it. &quot;
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As a Guildford music director since 1962, Vernon &quot;Tod&quot; Handley (obituary, 9/11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
As part of the district music plan, he founded the excellent youth choir Proteus a year later.
He was supposed to be under 21, but by the time Proteus last sang in 1979, there were almost 30 of us - we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name &quot;Proteus&quot; (mythological changer of shapes) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to play any music presented to it - whether madrigals or Messiaen, either alone or with the whole orchestra.
The musical adaptability created by such a young choir was often stunning, always exciting, all thanks to the inspiration of that one man and the passion for music that remained completely unchanged at all times.
How often has Tod told us to &quot;let the music speak for itself.&quot;
He said: &quot;The composer knows what he wants.
It&#39;s all in that music.
Then sing it! &quot;
His baton technique was perfectly clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the musical standard was, it always raised it.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If a conductor was to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well for two decades, when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
I&#39;ve reviewed more than 100 of his concerts in the last 40 years, and I can honestly say that I&#39;ve never been disappointed by any of them - and I&#39;ve been inspired many times.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of size and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply &quot;pulled one or two soaked stones around the world.&quot;
Many of us will miss it.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary William Woodruff (September 25) states that &quot;he returned to economic history in Oxford in 1946 and became a researcher at Houblon-Norman in 1950 ... while studying at BSc, MA and PhD&quot;.
This is based on Woodruff&#39;s author&#39;s note in Beyond Nab End, but it is not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953, he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, at which time he completed a dissertation on the British rubber industry, led by Professor JD Chambers, and subsequently published it in 1958 as the British Rubber Industry.
He actually spent 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at the University of Illinois, Harvard and New York University.
In 1953, he left Nottingham for good and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff went through this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated after the Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, of the Austrian right-wing Free Party, and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party are taking part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008, &quot;Cities Against Islamization&quot;.
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that show mosques crossed out with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties made huge profits in the general election.
More than 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were severely damaged sometime between Friday night and this morning, and police are convinced that it was an organized event.
The culprits spray-painted Jewish symbols on some graves, such as the Star of David, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to disguise the motives of extremists led by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether this incident was in any way connected with the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were &quot;deeply shocked&quot; by reports of desecration coming as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan drew to a close.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering a round of searching for its own soul after swinging to the right in yesterday&#39;s parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties, which together won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Free Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, led a vehement anti-immigration campaign, and some of their slogans were condemned by critics as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the Free Party, which won more than 18 percent of the vote, protested against scarves and burqas in the campaign, and even expressed his opposition to foods perceived to be related to Islam.
At the last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a &quot;European brotherhood&quot; to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Surveys and analyzes carried out immediately after the elections, which put the extreme right in the country&#39;s strongest political bloc, suggest that this change was mainly due to young voters worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed on a trip across the border
Gary Glitter, a glamrock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after informing monitoring authorities that he planned to travel via France to Spain.
The Kent police approved the travel ban last Thursday after handing over evidence to officials of Glitter&#39;s past convictions for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford&#39;s Lower Criminal Court in Kent, but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the judiciary said: &quot;On Thursday, September 25, the Ashford police asked Kent police for an order that would prevent Mr. Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until March 25.
Paul Gadd did not attend in person. &quot;
Glitter, 64, informed the authorities that he wished to travel abroad, as required by a record in the register of sexual assailants.
He must notify the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also pass the scheduled departure date to the police one week in advance.
If he neglected the obligation to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent police have said they will not discuss individual cases of Glitter&#39;s possible trips around the district.
A Kent police spokeswoman said: &quot;Kent police will do everything in their power to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it is easier to follow someone who stays in Britain, because we have extensive systems here that manage potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting the people of Kent is a top priority for the Kent police, and we are working hard to monitor the behavior of recorded sexual assailants to minimize any danger to the public. &quot;
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls between the ages of 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok, where he was to board a flight to London.
But he said he was not feeling well and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities did not let him pass passport control and eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to allow him entry, and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
He finally arrived at Heathrow&#39;s Terminal 3 on 22 August and remained there, while his lawyer, David Corker, went to the Uxbridge Lower Criminal Court in West London, while Scotland Yard successfully demanded an order ordering him to register as a sexual assailant.
Glitter was previously imprisoned in the United Kingdom for four months for possession of child pornography.
An Interior Ministry source said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was calm and glad that Glitter had been prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
&quot;To capture the real character, I take a picture of the master off stage.&quot; Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no ruffles or costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from concentrating on interpretation - only then will I achieve a relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other - man.
Inseparable, apart from privacy, in those moments far from the audience - then one can see an intimate gesture, the depth of a glimpse or a passionate gesture of hands that are carefree because they are not going to appear on stage.
In &quot;Flamenco-people&quot;, the German Günther Bauer alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer compiles a unique iconography of flamenco from various backgrounds.
The exhibition, part of the Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca program, &quot;reflects the growing international importance of flamenco,&quot; says the author, explaining that &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; &quot;can be any people, but when you look at the photos , you will find that these are not typical pictures of artists on stage.
These people portrayed &quot;on the street&quot; are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage ... and completely captivate the audience.
It is not necessary to take photos on stage to capture the personality of these artists.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that will allow me to capture the personality of the greats of flamenco.
Enchanted by the &quot;Cante de las Minas&quot; festival, in 1997 Bauer began a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The use of different stylistic means contradicts the classic basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, which is an idea that flamenco, according to Bauer himself, reflects: &quot;Music with very traditional roots, which, however, continues to surprise and evolve.&quot;
What captivates the audience is not the effect of the dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perceiving, being and experiencing, has been and is a constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
This selection of almost seventy artists photographed is made up of well-known flamenco figures, such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon have a book edition containing exhibited portraits.
Two years ago, Bauer&#39;s passion for portraiture led to the idea of repeating the idea in &quot;Portraits of Sports Veterans&quot; (&quot;SportARTproject&quot;).
Although their concept is different from &quot;Flamenco-people&quot;, the photographer admits that &quot;taking pictures of people, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a moment, whether longer or short - is my passion.
I think that photography is the most difficult genre in photography.
One meets or clashes with people, personalities who sometimes don&#39;t even know, or give him only a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas. &quot;
A collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; is on display in the El Fotómata Gallery at 20 de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
