Honda will attack with its bestseller for the second time
In November, Honda will launch the second generation Jazz.
If the predecessor of this one-compartment vehicle already had considerable space, it now offers an even more spacious interior.
To this are added improved engines that increase driving comfort and enable greater fuel savings.
Evolution rather than revolution.
Such is the second generation of Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically the lines of the new Jazz are very similar to the previous model, there have been many changes to this one-seater car.
It is necessary to mention, for example, the innovative design, the new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
Before examining the new model, it should be noted that the new Jazz is coming to the market six years after the launch of the first generation.
Therefore, the first thing we notice is the fact that Honda needed a shorter period to rejuvenate this model than other manufacturers.
Although Jazz is a lesser-known model in Europe, it has become a sales phenomenon in other markets.
This is the case in Japan, the country where the Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002, and also during this year 2008.
In Japan alone, almost a million units have been sold since the launch of the Honda Jazz.
The second market is the old continent, with about half a million units sold in six years.
However, Honda aims for the new Jazz to increase sales in its category.
So while in 2007 the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 Honda Jazzs, in 2009 estimates are estimated at 100,000 cars, an increase of 17% on the European market.
As for the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 Jazz models since 2002, representing 6.7% of Honda&#39;s total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation of Jazz, the management of the Spanish branch expects to sell 2,000 units for the whole year.
It is the arrival of the new Jazz that will allow Honda to significantly mitigate the decline in sales in Spain.
The carmaker&#39;s management thus de facto expects the end of the year with a total of 22,000 units sold, which means 4,000 less than in 2007 and a decrease of 16%.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda increased its share of the Spanish market to 1.8%, compared to 1.6% last year.
In 2010, the Japanese company expects to reach 2%.
To achieve this share, Honda relies on the success of its next new model.
It is the Honda Insight, a five-door compact hybrid with a length of 4.37 meters, from which the Japanese company promises worldwide sales of approximately 200,000 units per year.
In terms of markets, the Japanese manufacturer estimates that 50% of Insight will be sold in the United States, while the remaining percent will be shared between the old continent and Japan.
The Honda Insight is expected to go on sale in the first months of next year when it is unveiled to the public in Valencia in January.
Compared to the first generation, all dimensions of the new Jazz have increased.
Its length has increased to 3.9 meters (five centimeters more), width to 1.69 meters (two centimeters more) and wheelbase to 2.5 meters, which means an extension of five centimeters.
The height, on the other hand, has not changed and is still 1.52 meters.
The increase in dimensions also increased the interior space.
This advantage was achieved both by using a new platform and by placing a fuel tank in the middle of the car, which was already used in the previous Honda Jazz.
The volume of the luggage compartment - which has a double bottom system - has also increased to 399 liters, 19 liters more than the volume of the luggage compartment of the first generation.
It should be noted that these dimensions occur in the version with the 1.4 engine, as the volume of the luggage compartment of the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 liters.
Another improvement, in addition to external elements - such as LED rear lights or the possibility of being equipped with a glass panoramic roof - is easier access to the rear seats.
The door leading to the second row of seats allows an opening angle of 80 degrees compared to 67 in the first Jazz model.
The engines of the second generation Honda Jazz are also new.
Initially, this small model will be offered with two 1.2 and 1.4 liter petrol engines.
Both engines use i-VTEC technology, which enables lower fuel consumption, lower carbon dioxide emissions and excellent powertrain improvements along with high torque over the full engine speed range.
The first 1.2-liter engine has 90 horsepower at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had 78 horsepower in the previous generation Jazz - consumes 5.3 liters and emits 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous engine, which in the previous generation reached 83 horsepower, the current will reach 100.
The 100-horsepower Honda Jazz 1.4 has a combined consumption of 5.4 liters and emits 128 grams of CO2.
