&quot;Car bee&quot; prevents collisions
This time, Nissan was inspired to advance the development of accident protection technologies in nature, specifically in bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the example of flying bees and thus prevents collisions.
Such is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Nissan Motor Co. Center for Technical Progress Engineers The robot was developed in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Scientific Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doi, General Director of Public Relations for Brand Technology, Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan&#39;s four security shield zones.
The robot&#39;s task is to strengthen the ability of collision prevention in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval personal space, which closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
The most important, however, are the compound bee&#39;s eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
Engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder to create this visual feature.
It records obstacles up to two meters within 180 degrees of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
&quot;As soon as an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee&#39;s movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels at a right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, &quot;explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and the direction allowed by the rotation of its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
Therefore, in addition to accelerating and decelerating, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
&quot;The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and behave according to this data.
It does not require the retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we&#39;re not talking about gigas or mega-minds. &quot;
This is the first step in the development of new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan is predicting to use in production cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate the unit into a GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
Drivers repeatedly caught with blood alcohol will need to install an &quot;alcolock&quot;
The Ministry of the Interior requires a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol to have to install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car while drunk or not breathing.
The proposal became known as early as June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Public Prosecutor&#39;s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its aim is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a traffic re-education course.
In addition to the National Office for Traffic Safety, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Automotive Safety (FITSA) will also take part in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists charged more than once for drunk driving will again get behind the wheel in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe beforehand or if a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is detected.
Its price exceeds 1,000 euros and the culprit himself would have to pay for it.
A study carried out in this regard in the USA in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device had a 65% reduction in offenses during the first year since its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could save lives every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behavior before it results in a criminal offense.
And in order to help its implementation, as the legislation can be implemented in the usual way, but the necessary adjustment of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available in any commercial version on the Spanish market, although it has already been trial-installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a proposal by the PSOE (Spanish Socialist Workers&#39; Party), which recommends installing this system in school buses, as is the case in France.
