Talking from sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don&#39;t mean those who wake up and actively tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you, but in reality it is irrelevant.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somnolence.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly many of you were told that he was talking about sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason to explain her onset.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nightmares, enuresis nocturna (night urination) or drowsiness, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or aggravated situations.
In any case, this is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs also varies.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or vice versa (screams, crying, long speeches ...).
In cases where it manifests with great force, it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult an expert to see if he has a problem that causes him great anxiety and manifests itself in this way.
We have said that it is a harmless disorder, so it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to upset the child too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who are given a job to relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain a certain inner peace.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
When somnolence appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything from what happened the next day.
Useful advice
Don&#39;t be him.
It is useless because he is unconscious and you interrupt his sleep.
Although he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Remember that if you find yourself bothered several times in a row, it would be useful to seek advice or find out what is causing your anxiety.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and pull information from him.
It will be useless, because when he sleeps, he is not conscious so that he can organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he thinks about, and therefore why he says it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you come to.
Never tell your child that you can ask him his secrets at night.
Not for fun.
This causes great anxiety.
Don&#39;t worry, it&#39;s not a bad thing, it&#39;s just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
