&quot;At that time, we saw many cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,&quot; says the woman, who has run the company since its inception in 1998.
&quot;And we had no idea if the disease could spread through the blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, when we do not know it and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusionary measures need to be taken.
In April 1999, therefore, we rejected blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted through blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the precautionary principle. &quot;
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests used previously were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the dead time that occurs between the moment the patient becomes infected and the moment when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
In this way, we have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could become infected without knowing it and without knowing it.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
&quot;In other words, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone can get HIV.
Because Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to occur.
I think that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for healing in complete peace of mind, &quot;says the head of the Héma-Québek management.
&quot;The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what pathogenic element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stinging insects.
We need to be constantly vigilant, &quot;Dr. Décary continues, stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also count on a sufficient supply.
&quot;Needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecs eligible for donation. &quot;
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can only donate blood once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is rampant, they are excluded for one year.
&quot;With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, persuading people to donate blood is difficult, especially keeping them and encouraging them to become regular donors.
Life today is so unfettered that we seldom find an hour to donate blood, &quot;laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $ 297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québek, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
Formerly considered biomedical waste, the umbilical cord is rich in stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
&quot;A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample in a bank, and we expect to take over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants, &quot;explains Dr. Décary, who describes the umbilical cord blood collection program as very popular.
&quot;Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it,&quot; because Héma-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
