Opinions - Barrick Gold&#39;s Orwell Discourse
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwell&#39;s logic, he confirms that the world&#39;s largest gold producer has prosecuted three authors and a poor small publishing house for defamation to provoke a &quot;transparent public debate&quot; and is demanding six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver completely ignores this fundamental distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct a public debate, to bring to ruin anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend respectable sums in order to be prepared to defend and fight in a very unbalanced battle with an army of lawyers backed by almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic in these unbalanced battles, moreover, often consists in the bankruptcy of the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure, which will close the mouth of the other party and, moreover, frighten anyone who would dare to do so.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its point of view to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate is normally about exchanging ideas, not batons.
So all the mining companies had to do were open their books, their documentation, and set up a real debate through newspapers, the media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and has flatly rejected petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a &quot;public debate&quot; while despising the views of the same public?
In the Vice President&#39;s world, the word seems to refer only to bold lawyers, not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow conception of the term.
In a democracy, even nightmares have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, which supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and assess the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many see as a prosecution to put the defendant&#39;s mouth shut (in the prosecution of &quot;public debate&quot;, Barrick has just given a formal call the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them that they should stop using this term ...).
Leaving aside Garver&#39;s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university&#39;s freedom of research and the search for truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that are the very basis of intellectual activity.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that are not pleased with the rich companies of this world without being repeatedly prosecuted, who else can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have formed it if it had followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold&#39;s exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of unjustified prosecution.
Wall Street rescue operations - Democrats and Republicans understand
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to curb the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months with $ 700 billion has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure repayment of public money, new measures to capture the number of houses confiscated for non-payment, and the right to monitor the level of salaries paid to executives of rescued companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican leader Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday, after midnight, after the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
&quot;We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets,&quot; said the Bush administration&#39;s chief, Henry Paulson.
&quot;Everything has been done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the Wall Street crisis,&quot; the Democrat explained.
&quot;This is a crucial point: if we do not, the trauma, chaos and disruption of Americans&#39; daily lives will be enormous,&quot; said Republican Judd Gregg.
In the last few hours, negotiations have been in full swing for fear of the effect that another failure would have on the mood of investors.
The set time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both US presidential candidates were invited to the negotiations later, and both were more in favor of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such a last resort.
Democratic Sen. Barack Obama has noted that the agreement has been supplemented by some measures, in particular to enable homeowners to retain their residence, and measures on the salaries of managers of state-rescued companies.
&quot;When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate.
However, these measures are necessary, &quot;he explained on television.
His Republican rival, John McCain, who was asked by another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: &quot;I would like to see the details, but I hope so.&quot;
&quot;The rough features I&#39;ve read [show] that this is something we will all have to spend and move forward with.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable, &quot;he said.
The goal of the $ 700 billion plan is to buy out dubious receivables and risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions for taxpayers&#39; money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprimes, then moved to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
Republican deputies are responsible for the collapse of last week&#39;s first draft agreement.
Ever since Democrats agreed that some &quot;toxic&quot; assets of troubled companies would only be liable by the government but would not buy them out, there is a belief that the impasse has been averted.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, a measure has been added stating that the government will be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it has to bear losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan envisages a first deposit of 250 billion, to which another 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire stakes in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends in the event of a profit, and which he will be able to resell when it&#39;s all over.
The federal government will be able to delay the foreclosure procedures associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of valuations and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The planners would like to put it to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against this project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
&quot;Obviously, Washington can&#39;t hear you,&quot; Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
&quot;Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money on taxpayers is not the answer. &quot;
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a group of congressmen nicknamed the &quot;Skeptics Committee,&quot; presents the matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
&quot;Four hundred esteemed professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, wrote to us: We ask Congress not to hurry too much and to examine carefully which way to go,&quot; he said yesterday.
At the same time, it has been reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a world crisis.
Following the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion USD).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the verge of collapse since losing 2 billion euros (2.9 billion USD) due to the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is one of the twenty largest European banks and one of the ten largest insurers.
&quot;We will not lose this money,&quot; Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
&quot;In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And this is exactly what savers and households can appreciate in today&#39;s uncertain times. &quot;
On the other side of the English Channel, the British government seems to have begun nationalizing another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion ($ 75.5 billion) were loans for the purchase of real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock that the British government must nationalize since the beginning of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - The death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with azure eyes had long been his trump card, others weakness.
Did this American actor with a charming smile break free from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and unrelenting talent that was inherent in him also distanced him from the power category that breeds real stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 on his ranch in Connecticut of lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less magnificent than Brando, to whom he was like and for a long time somehow his rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often gives birth to beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it saw the whole country in love with self-made mana, a war warrior in the Pacific, wounded in battle, who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s, then attended New York&#39;s Actor&#39;s Studio and celebrated a triumph in theater, television and soon in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also the second car racer to compete in the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 1979, and a sex symbol, despite having been a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958. .
With him also leave the shadows of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of his own show business, which will forever remain to some extent mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman&#39;s departure this weekend has made the film&#39;s lovers dizzy, while his big roles compete with each other on the black screen of memories.
After it, more than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art parades.
A charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) reappears in his memory, a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From the less distant past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, disturbed at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans went down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, Robert Wise&#39;s battered, violent, unforgettable offender from Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role for James Dean, taken over after his death, which made Newman truly famous in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, an Oscar for best film in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful snooker player in the amazing The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961), he plays the same character in Martin Scorsese&#39;s The Color of Money, which will bring him the only Oscar of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering the ages, it was him.
And he again.
In his career, different epochs compete with each other.
Young people know him mainly thanks to the cult Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, a non-traditional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 at The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He then ended his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes&#39; Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the craft relatively soon, Newman remained in the industry for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood with its tinsel, pomp, and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humor, considered it &quot;a living challenge of underplaying&quot;, judging that in his performances he put too much pressure on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
However, he played the first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, thugs and desperate people, whose declines and rebellions were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensitivity.
His Rachel film, 1968&#39;s Rachel (based on the Canadian novel by Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, presents a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the film Harry and Son, a work full of shame and sadness, to his son Scott, whom he lost due to an overdose.
In a flurry of honors that Newman received yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (who played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said sadly, &quot;His presence has made my life and this country better.&quot;
Generosity, love of life, such are the main qualities of a deceased actor.
Leaving aside his legendary career, the great fighter for civil rights, ecology, independent film and opponents of Hollywood&#39;s decline are also leaving.
We used to see his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which may have seemed quite tasteless, although at first it was a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Hard Childhood Foundation.
Newman thus engaged in society until the last moment, rather than being swayed by fame.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing the following sentences: &quot;Always and until the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
I was honored to be here. &quot;
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the career of such a clairvoyant and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, an exemplary citizen.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; spol.?
Soon, on October 8, the trial will begin in criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates.
In addition to other crimes, including forgery of documents, a politician and his associates are accused of fraud committed on a long-term and systematic basis by a criminal organization, which has resulted in extremely significant damage.
According to the prosecutor&#39;s office, they used the money obtained in public tenders for their own purposes and often proved the fulfillment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
Money from the state and local governments - a total of about 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method, which was also reported by the investigating authority, was that the money obtained in the tenders was collected on the basis of invoices, for which there was no real consideration, and the associations never received the commitments entered into.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
The forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, round stamps were made in Kiskunhalas.
The names of which companies the invoices should be produced were decided, among other things, on a round trip along the northern shore of Lake Balaton, to which János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
According to his statement, the former was to look for guesthouses and restaurants.
In them, he applied for bills for his consumption, according to whose model invoices submitted in public tenders issued by, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, and the Municipal Government, respectively, were produced.
Invoices were mostly issued by István Lados and his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
During his &quot;study trip&quot;, Lados found a beer hall.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, the hospitality establishment provided catering for a group of 90 from the Biztos Pont association.
However, according to the head of the company, so many people would not fit into this facility at once.
