The Psychology of Trump: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, revaluation of goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have been able to uncover the neurological and economic underpinnings of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in an eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research used an experimental auction to try to map the scheme of this &quot;game&quot; in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a feature auction, and the active areas of the subjects&#39; brains were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, an important element of which is to overpower the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively during the game.
This area of the brain plays, among many other functions, a role in the &quot;self-rewarding&quot; mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the unscrewing of the price can therefore be explained by the effort to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists conducted a cross-sectional financial survey.
Under different conditions, three groups bid against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive another $ 15 in reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $ 15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, then, was that one emphasized winning and the other losing.
However, the members of the group playing &quot;against the loss&quot; were willing to go higher than in the control and &quot;winning&quot; group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
&quot;These results cannot be deduced from any pre - existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained the phenomena observable at auctions of the joys of victory and avoiding risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the discrepancy between the two theories, so that we have now reached the third explanation, &quot;said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University&#39;s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are being treated. This is because patients often do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, hepatitis and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (eg infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva). .
Travelers should in any case be protected by vaccination against A and B virus, there is no vaccine against type C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating an infected meal, and are usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, and nausea.
Then jaundice, lightened stools and urine darken on the skin and whites of the eyes. The treatment can last for two to three weeks.
Every year, millions of people around the world die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people infected do not even know about their disease, the pathogen insidiously destroys liver cells, so the first symptoms appear in many cases in 20-30 years.
That is why early prevention, regular screening, is very important.
In three groups, the disease is much more common than average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can already be demonstrated by routine laboratory tests, one should consult a general practitioner if he or she experiences any symptoms of unknown origin.
Upon early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infectivity and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized worldwide in 2004 by organizations representing patients.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, to the causes of its occurrence and to the importance of early detection of the disease.
