A smart car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would probably be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing a collision, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the natural world?
For example, in bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese trade fair CEATEC, was inspired by engineers from Nissan by bumblebees. It was about building a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed the BR23C-type biomimetic robotic steering system, a robotic mini-car equipped with bee features, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
&quot;During the flight, each bee creates its own oval personal space, which is very similar to our safety cover,&quot; explained Kazuhiro Doi, brand CEO for technology PR and research and development, at the show.
An important role is played by compound eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
Engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder to copy the function of the compound eye.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is captured in a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to mimic the bee&#39;s movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
&quot;If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees by avoidance, in the case of the robotic car only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and deceleration was used.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means that they have a longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, the important thing is instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, much less data storage.
This mechanism only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to store and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only a few kilobytes of memory.
It does not need memory with gigabit or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of instant avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced cars in ten years.
Another possible application may be to connect the unit to a GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
