Fox in a chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of taking out an insurance contract with a candidate based on people&#39;s information about buying drugs.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
&quot;There is a data protection program which links the use of prescription medicines in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
He must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to the fox, &quot;the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, the author of a program designed to monitor prescription drugs.
Insurance companies make premiums and amounts paid in the event of insured events dependent on the health status of the applicants, and if the risk is assessed as too great, they will not even take out insurance with it.
Previously, they sent those concerned for medical examinations and contracted only when they knew the results.
Ten years ago, Dick devised a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the customer could easily find out from the pharmacies what drugs he had bought in the last year and a half, from which the program himself deduced his illness and condition.
For example, if he regularly buys a large amount of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it indicates that he has virtually uncontrollably high levels of blood fats, which immediately puts him in a higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which also determine the risk coefficient, so that the insurance company has almost no work left, apart from paperwork, although minor problems arise.
Disadvantages include the fact that many drugs can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds are useful against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-increasing factor, while the former do not.
In order to request and process the data, special companies have been set up to ask the patient&#39;s permission before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, although they have not punished them for their negligence.
Some companies have recently been processing the results of laboratory tests, which are combined with data on the drugs used, thanks to which they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients&#39; health.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it will be more and more difficult to control their use.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness only applies to health care providers and insurance companies.
A bill that will give authorities the power to control companies specializing in providing data is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his program in such a way that the transfer of data is subject to the express consent of the person concerned.
