This new emphase, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, moreover, in full accordance with the growing importance which recent economic advances are trying to attribute to one factor closely linked to it: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the network, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, we realized out of nowhere that our future would have to increasingly struggling with such little intangible things as water, grain, oil.
