I come to the second novelty, which, however, predicts a turning point.
Whoever speaks of territory, state, government, inevitably speaks of politics, that is, leadership.
Taking into account the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena seem to be emerging.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, a request for someone who can take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit against existing leadership, especially economic leadership, which has proved to be equally unsatisfactory and full of dark spots.
And together, something even deeper and, in a sense, disturbing: discredit, impatience, a sense of incompetence, and an absence that seeks to control the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
