Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso, the city is abolished by historic halls
Cinematographic historical halls close in favor of the Multiplex.
&quot;A city without cinemas is like a blind man, it&#39;s like a face without eyes.&quot;
The painting offered by director Giuseppe Tornator successfully documents what is happening in large Italian urban centers, but also in rural towns.
The process of reducing cinemas, the birth of large multi-halls in the suburbs and the subsequent demise of monos halls in the central zones of cities is one of the events that seem inevitable and irreversible, but it also has all the hallmarks of a real cultural crime.
Historical places full of memories often disappear, &quot;it&#39;s as if we lost a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a long way and a lot of emotions&quot;, feels the director of the New Paradiso Cinema, a film that won the Oscar and Grand Jury Prize twenty years ago. Cannes, and which told the poetry of a village cinema and the grief of a way of life that the cinema must have lost forever.
The values gained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak for themselves: in the last five years, 316 traditional-type cinemas have closed the doors, and the highest bills have been paid mainly by halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Torino, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna ranks first with the loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the proof that the first to be responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex is precisely the three Italian regions that have registered the highest number of new cinema multiplexes: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna .
&quot;The Italian process has evolved irrationally,&quot; says Paolo Protti, president of Anecu, &quot;it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that existing ones survive, because when one cinema in the city closes, not all its visitors are willing to relocate to multiplex.
Then let&#39;s not even talk about the insufficient subsidy to the fund in favor of the operators: the previous state debt is about 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between € 16 and € 18 million a year would be needed to support the sector ».
Interesting is the Bologna case, the first Italian city to deal with closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas in both historic centers and suburbs.
Among the planned standards are tax relief steps in favor of operators and benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special prices to stop and in some car parks.
&quot;I like this initiative,&quot; says Giuseppe Tornatore, &quot;and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures.&quot;
However, it is certain that in order to oppose the great power of the multiplex, traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and image, because today&#39;s audience is more demanding.
Defending traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was a spark that convinced me to start the &quot;New Paradiso Cinema&quot;, which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I&#39;ve lived in Rome for 25 years, and as I walk in front of the already closed Rialto or Quirinal on Nazionale Street, where I&#39;ve shared so much emotion that I don&#39;t have to look at dust-blackened inscriptions, I turn the other way.
